        <h3>1.2 Layouts</h3>

            <p>
                Descovrir takes a layout-specified approach rather than a column-specified approach. There are essentially <strong>five types of layouts</strong> present in most web designs. Layouts can be nested within each other.
            </p>

            <p>
                Any element may be set to a specific number of columns, using the class <code>col-n</code>. Any element with set columns larger than the available screen will be reduced to the maximum width.
            </p>

            <p>
                <em>&sect;11 Page Layouts</em> describes some common use cases of layout combinations.
            </p>

            <h3>1.2.1 Full Width Layout</h3>

                <p>
                    A full-width element assumes the width of its parent. Full-width is native to block level elements, but can be manually set by <code>full-width</code>.
                </p>


            <h3>1.2.2 Max Width Layout</h3>

                <p>
                    A max-width element will assume the width of its parent up to a specified number of columns. Max width is set by the class <code>max-width-n</code>. Prefer max-widths set in two, four, six...
                </p>

            <h3>1.2.3 Serial Layout</h3>

                <p>
                    A serial layout consists of a set of even-width elements. Serial layouts specify a maximum number of columns per element.
                </p>

                <p>
                    Wrap the elements in a <code>div</code> of <code>serial-n</code>, where <var>n</var> is the number of columns from one to eight, not the number of elements.
                </p>

            <h3>1.2.4 Aside Layout</h3>

                <p>
                    An aside, either on the left or right side, of one to six columns. The main element will take the rest of the parent's width. When the main is less than 60% of the parent, both the main and the aside appear in full width. For a two-in-one aside, use the serial layout inside the aside.
                </p>

                <p>
                    Wrap both <code>main</code> and <code>aside</code> in a <code>div</code> with the class <code>aside-d-n</code>, where <var>d</var> is either <em>left</em> or <em>right</em>, and <var>n</var> is the number of columns of the aside.
                </p>

            <h3>1.2.5 Double Aside Layout</h3>

                <p>
                    Two asides appear with the main content, one on the left and one on the right. Each aside is one to five columns. The main element takes the remaining space. If the main element is less than 60% of the parent, all three elements are in full width. The sum of the aside columns must be six or less.
                </p>

                <p>
                    Create container <code>aside-left-dl-right-dr</code>, where <var>dl</var> is the number of left columns and <var>dr</var> is the number of right columns. Create an <code>aside</code>, <code>main</code>, and <code>aside</code> elements within the container.
                </p>

