    <h2>3. Typography</h2>

        <h3>3.1 Font stacks</h3>

            <p>
                Descovrir's primary typeface is Palatino. Monospaced typography uses DejaVu Sans Mono derivatives. When necessary, Lucida can be used as a san-serif typeface. Note Lucida does not support true italics on several operating systems.
            </p>

            <ul>
                <li><strong>Base</strong>: "palatino linotype", palatino, palladio, "urw palladio l", "book antiqua", serif</li>
                <li class="monospace"><strong>Monospace</strong>: menlo, "dejavu sans mono", "bitstream vera sans mono", consolas, inconsolata, "lucida console", monaco, monospace</li>
                <li class="sans-serif"><strong>Sans-serif</strong>: "lucida grande", "lucida sans unicode", "lucida sans", geneva, sans-serif</li>
            </ul>

            <p>
                The classes <code>base-font</code>, <code>monospace</code>, and <code>sans-serif</code> can be used to alter the typeface.
            </p>

        <h3>3.2 Headings, Subheadings, and Header Groups</h3>

            <p>
                All elements <code>h1</code> through <code>h6</code> are styled.
            </p>

            <figure>

                <h1>h1. A Page Level Heading</h1>

                <h2>h2. A Section Level Heading</h2>

                <h3>h3. A Subsection Level Heading</h3>

                <h4>h4. A Division Level Heading</h4>

                <h5>h5. Additional Level Heading</h5>

                <h6>h6. Small Level Heading</h6>

            </figure>

            <p>
                Sub-headers use the class <code>subheader</code> when used directly below a higher order header. An <code>hgroup</code> collapses the margins between the headers.
            </p>

            <figure>

                <hgroup>
                    <h1>h1. A Page Level Heading</h1>
                    <h2 class="subheader">h2. A subtitle of h1</h2>
                    <h3 class="subheader">h3. And a third level title</h3>
                </hgroup>

            </figure>

            <h4>3.2.1 Small inline elements with headers</h4>

                <p>
                    Optionally, elements can float along with the header. The most easy way to accomplish this is to wrap the header in an <code>hgroup</code> and add the class <code>inline-block</code> to the header tag.
                </p>

                <figure>
                    <hgroup>
                        <h1 class="inline-block push-right">h1. A Page Level Heading</h1>
                        <a href="#"><i class="icon-heart"></i>An additional link</a>
                    </hgroup>
                </figure>

    <h2>4. Inline-level tags</h2>

        <h3>4.1 Links</h3>

            <p>
                Links are simply blue in color, and like other states, <em>lighten</em> on hover and focus, and <em>darken</em> on active (clicked) or selected. Icons can be optionally included in links. Links stay underlined to support the color. Visited links receive no extraordinary treatment.
            </p>

            <ul>
                <li><a href="#">Normal link</a></li>
                <li><a href="#" class="hover">Hovered or focused link</a></li>
                <li><a href="#" class="selected">Active or selected link</a></li>
            </ul>

        <h3>4.2 Small, Strong, Emphasis, Deletion, Insertion, Mark, Subscript, Superscript, Abbreviations, and Code</h3>

            <p>
                All normal tag operations are supported and provide expected results. Note that <code>b</code>, <code>s</code>, and <code>u</code> tags are not supported, and <code>i</code> tags are reserved for icons, not italics.
            </p>

            <ul>
                <li><strong>A strong element</strong></li>
                <li><em>An emphasized element</em></li>
                <li><small>A small element</small></li>
                <li><del>A deleted element</del></li>
                <li><ins>An inserted element</ins></li>
                <li><mark>A marked element</mark></li>
                <li><sub>A subscript element</sub> and a normal element</li>
                <li><sup>A superscript element</sup> and a normal element</li>
                <li>An example abbreviation: <abbr data-title="Hypertext Transfer Protocol">HTTP</abbr></li>
                <li><code>Inline code element</code></li>
            </ul>

            <p>
                Other elements, such as <code>var</code>, <code>samp</code>, and <code>kbd</code>, are styled but non-effectively.
            </p>

        <h3>4.3 Defintion</h3>

            <p>
                The <code>dfn</code> element can be used on the defining instance of a term. It is often used with a title attribute with a defintion of the term.
            </p>

            <figure>
                An example definition of <dfn data-title="The perception of fluctuations of air pressure.">sound</dfn>.
            </figure>

        <h3>4.3 Time and Dates</h3>

            <p>
                The <code>time</code> tag is used to describe specific dates and times. It does not indicate durations. The <code>datetime</code> attribute is optional.
            </p>

        <h3>4.4 Inline Quotations and Citations</h3>

            <p>
                The <code>q</code> and <code>cite</code> tags are used together to indicate a quote and a citation. All quotes are cited. No quote marks are included when using the <code>q</code> tag.
            </p>

            <p>
                <q>Prior knowledge has a large influence on student performance, explaining up to 81 percent of the variance in post-test scores.</q> <cite>Dochy, Segers, and Buehl</cite>
            </p>

        <h3>4.5 Inline Labels</h3>

            <p>
                Labels are available in each of the basic hues.
            </p>

            <ul>
                <li>Error or Danger: <span class="label--error">label</span> and numeric label: <span class="label--error">100</span></li>
                <li>Default, Base or Warn: <span class="label--warn">label</span> and numeric label: <span class="label--warn">100</span></li>
                <li>Success or Accept: <span class="label--accept">label</span> and numeric label: <span class="label--accept">100</span></li>
                <li>Accent or Info: <span class="label--info">label</span> and numeric label: <span class="label--info">100</span></li>
                <li>Official or Admin: <span class="label--official">label</span> and numeric label: <span class="label--official">100</span></li>
            </ul>

    <h2>5. Block-level tags</h2>

        <h3>5.1 Paragraphs</h3>

            <p>
                Paragraphs follow standard conventions. Paragraphs have a default maximum width to improve readability. This can be overwritten using the <code>full-width</code> class.
            </p>

            <h4>5.1.1 Leading Paragraphs</h4>

            <p>
                Leading paragraphs, commonly used after the page title, emphasis a block of text. Often leading paragraphs are used to describe the page contents.
            </p>

            <p class="leading">
                An example paragraph in the leading style.
            </p>

        <h3>5.2 Lists</h3>

            <h4>5.2.1 Unordered Lists</h4>

                <p>
                    Unordered lists follow standard conventions. Line items do not hold extra margins. Only root-level unordered lists have a bottom margin.
                </p>

                <ul>
                    <li>Item 1
                        <ul>
                            <li>Item 1.1</li>
                            <li>Item 1.2</li>
                            <li>Item 1.3</li>
                        </ul>
                    </li>
                    <li>Item 2</li>
                    <li>Item 3</li>
                </ul>

            <h4>5.2.2 Ordered Lists</h4>

                <p>
                    Ordered lists follow the standard conventions as well.
                </p>

                <ol>
                    <li>Item 1
                        <ul>
                            <li>Item 1.1</li>
                            <li>Item 1.2</li>
                            <li>Item 1.3</li>
                        </ul>
                    </li>
